To understand how the Event Loop handles a large file with 200 lines of code, synchronous functions, 3 to 4 API network calls, and 3 to 4 file reads, you have to look at it in two distinct stages: Initialization and Asynchronous Execution.Phase 1: The Initialization Stage (The Call Stack)When you run node app.js, Node.js does not start the Event Loop immediately. It first processes the entire file from line 1 to 200 on the Call Stack (Synchronous Thread).Synchronous Functions: Any standard functions, loops, or math calculations run immediately. They block the thread until they are completely finished.3–4 File Reads (fs.readFile): Node.js passes these tasks to the libuv Thread Pool (background threads). The Main Thread does not wait; it instantly moves to the next line.3–4 API Calls (fetch / axios): Node.js passes these to the Operating System network stack in the background. Again, the Main Thread moves on instantly.At line 200, the Call Stack is empty. Only now does the Event Loop spin up and take control.Phase 2: The Event Loop Stage (The Race)The Event Loop now enters a continuous cycle, rotating through its standard phases to check if any background operations have finished.Because file reads and network calls take different amounts of time, their callbacks enter the Event Loop in a race condition based on speed.Here is how the Event Loop processes them as they finish:text ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │ 1. TIMERS PHASE                                        │
 │    - Checks for expired setTimeout/setInterval         │
 └───────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┘
