Use code with caution.1. Handling the API Calls (Network I/O)What happens: Your operating system handles the HTTP requests.Event Loop Phase: When a website responds, the OS flags it. The Event Loop picks up the callback during the Poll Phase and executes the code inside your .then() or async/await block.2. Handling the File Reads (Disk I/O)What happens: Node's background thread pool reads the files from your hard drive.Event Loop Phase: As soon as a file is read into memory, its callback is placed into the I/O queue. The Event Loop processes it during the Poll Phase.Crucial Rule: The Order is "First Come, First Served"If File Read #2 is a tiny 1KB file, and File Read #1 is a massive 500MB file, File Read #2 will execute its callback first.The Event Loop does not care about the order you wrote them in your 200 lines of code. It only cares about which background task finishes first.What happens if multiple tasks finish at the exact same millisecond?If an API call and a File Read finish at the exact same time, they both land in the Poll Phase queue. The Event Loop will simply process them one after the other in the order they arrived in that queue, without blocking the application.Would you like to see how a process.nextTick or a Promise microtask behaves if you insert it inside one of these API call callbacks?
